			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Having recently 'ding'ed to level 63, I now have the joy and frustration of having the <span style="color: red">Elemental Silence</span> spell.  I love being able to mez - for the first time in my career as a mage, I am able to save another person's hide or pull the group out of a bad situation <span style="font-style: italic">in one single zone in the entire game</span>.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, the level 60 limit on Elemental Silence means that it is almost random whether I will be able to mez something or not in a level 65 adventure.  I'd guess between 1/3 and 1/2 of the creatures in the dungeon are above level 60.  What this means, is that if I'm in a group that <span style="font-style: italic">requires</span> mezzing to be successful, we still need an enchanter or bard - I can't guarantee that we won't have 3-4 mobs on us that are completely unmezzable to me.  To add insult to injury (or vice versa I suppose since it usually results in injury to me...) the spell doesn't mention that a target is immune until AFTER casting and being resisted (with all the aggro a resisted mez entails).
<br />

<br />
I was about to resign myself to the fact that if you need crowd control, you need an enchanter/bard until I was grouped with a necromancer on a guk adventure and found out necros get the spell Death's Silence.  This spell is an undead specific mez that is identical to Elemental Silence (same level, mana cost, resist adjust, duration), except that unlike Elemental Silence, Death's Silence works on mobs up to level 65.  Now what I don't understand, is why is the magician anti-summoned mez specifically crippled by a level 60 cap if necromancers get the same thing versus undead that is not crippled?
<br />

<br />
The only explanation I could think of is that these spells were released with the PoP expansion.  At that time, there really wasn't any zone that was predominantly summoned creatures.  Thus, giving mages elemental silence was not intended to provide mages with the ability to do crowd control, but was in fact added for specific situational use.  Thus, ES wasn't specifically capped at level 60 to piss off mages in Takish Hiz adventures, but instead was capped there for other reasons likely related to PoP encounters.
<br />

<br />
Now that LDoN is out, and we have a zone that is predominantly summoned mobs, I wonder if there's some way to get SoE to reconsider the level cap on Elemental Silence?<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=597105" target="_blank" class="postlink">Master Belthil Telperion</a>
<br />
63 Magician, Erollisi Marr</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
